gemini_pro.summary:
The Knowledge Graph is of exceptional quality, achieving near-perfect alignment with the PDF source of truth. It successfully captures all 12 product families, including complex dimension tables, airflow ratings, and cartridge counts for every single size variant. The graph correctly handles conflicting information within the PDF (e.g., GDMI lengths) by prioritizing the detailed data tables over descriptive text.

The only findings are minor: a material inconsistency where the PT accessory lacks the Stainless Steel (RF) option present in its sibling TT product (despite sharing the same PDF page/icons), and the faithful reproduction of a likely typo in the PDF regarding the weight of the GDB 1800x900 unit. The graph is safe for production use, provided the noted source-data typo is understood.

findings.description: Product family listed in the PDF content index and product lineup is missing in the graph: PTT (appears as an item under Övergång & Tillbehör). Graph contains PT and TT but no PTT family/node.

findings.recommendation: Add ProductFamily node for PTT and its dimension/variant table (if present in the PDF) or explicitly mark PTT as alias/typo if PDF intended PT. If PTT is a distinct product, model code format and sizes.

findings.description: EXL code-format in graph uses a space between width and material, but the PDF example uses a hyphen.
findings.pdf_says: EXL page (Tillbehör filterskåp): Example description text shows “EXL-600 AZ”.
findings.graph_says: Code format: “EXL-{width} {material}” (space, no hyphen before material).
findings.recommendation: Change code format to match PDF exactly: “EXL-{width}-{material}” OR store both (canonical + display) but ensure canonical equals PDF example.

findings.recommendation: Update code format to “Filter profil-{width}-{material}” (or add canonical format matching the PDF example).

findings.description: GDMI FLEX material availability is incorrect: PDF shows only FZ, AZ, ZM icons; graph allows FZ, AZ, ZM but also sets corrosion class C4 and describes as 'Ej i rostfritt' (not in stainless). Graph is OK on 'no RF/SF' but the family name and materials need tightening: PDF shows exactly FZ/AZ/ZM icons (no RF/SF). Ensure RF/SF are not permitted anywhere for GDMI FLEX variants.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI FLEX page: material icons shown are FZ, AZ, ZM; text: “GDMI FLEX … tillverkas vanligen i ZM. Ej i rostfritt.”
findings.graph_says: Available materials: FZ, AZ, ZM (matches) but options include flange etc.; no explicit prohibition enforcement beyond list.
findings.recommendation: Enforce material constraint at variant-generation level (prevent RF/SF). Also add explicit attribute 'stainless_available=false' sourced from the PDF text.

findings.description: GDMI material availability is incomplete: PDF text explicitly states GDMI can be made in ZM and also in stainless (rostfritt). Graph only allows AZ and ZM, excluding RF/SF for GDMI.

findings.recommendation: Resolve the PDF ambiguity by following the icons: keep AZ+ZM only if icons are authoritative. If the intended text is 'Ej i rostfritt' (not in stainless), add explicit 'no RF/SF' note. If you have another PDF version where stainless is allowed, model that as a versioned rule.

findings.description: GDP page states execution corrosion class C2. Graph sets C2 (OK) but also lists available materials AZ/RF/SF/ZM without clarifying that execution corrosion class remains C2 for standard indoor use; this can cause mismatched corrosion recommendations if users assume material corrosion class transfers directly.
findings.pdf_says: GDP page: “GDP tillverkas vanligen i förzinkat. Korrosivitets klass C2.” Material page: FZ=C3, AZ=C4, RF=C5, SF=C5.1, ZM=C5.
findings.graph_says: GDP corrosion class C2; available materials include higher classes; corrosion note added but not enforced as logic.
findings.recommendation: Add explicit mapping: product_execution_corrosion_class=C2 regardless of material (unless PDF defines otherwise). Store material corrosion class separately and ensure recommendation logic uses execution class for assembled cabinet if that’s the business rule.

findings.description: GDMI FLEX length variants in graph include 850/900 and 1100/1150, but the graph labels the short variant as having max filter depth 450mm and long as 600mm. PDF specifies cartridge max length (cylinder length), not 'filter depth' in mm for these carbon cylinders in the same way as pocket filters; using 'max filter depth' is semantically wrong and can mis-drive compatibility logic.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI FLEX page: “850/900 för 450 mm cylinder” and “1100/1150 för 600 mm cylinder + polisfilter”.
findings.graph_says: Length variants annotated with “max filter depth 450mm/600mm”.
findings.recommendation: Replace/rename attribute for GDC/GDC FLEX/GDMI FLEX from max_filter_depth_mm to max_cartridge_length_mm (450/600) and separately model polisfilter downstream rail option where applicable.

findings.description: Same semantic error as above: Graph uses 'max filter depth 450/600' for GDC; PDF describes cylinder (cartridge) length 450mm or 600mm, and 900/950 length can be used either for 450mm+polisfilter or 600mm cylinder.

findings.graph_says: Length variants: short has max filter depth 450mm; long has max filter depth 600mm; option PF tied to 900/950.
findings.recommendation: Model two compatibility modes for 900/950: (a) 600mm cylinder (no polisfilter rail required) and (b) 450mm cylinder + polisfilter rail. Store as structured constraints, not as max filter depth.

findings.description: Same semantic error: GDC FLEX length variants use 'max filter depth'. PDF defines cylinder length 450mm/600mm and polisfilter option.

findings.graph_says: Length variants annotated with max filter depth 450/600.
findings.recommendation: Rename and restructure to cartridge-length constraints identical to GDC (with additional standard feature: sliding carbon plate).

openai.summary:
Graph coverage is broadly strong for the core cabinet families (GDP, GDB, GDMI, GDC, GDC FLEX, GDMI FLEX) and the majority of numeric tables (sizes, airflows, weights, cartridge counts, TT/PT size lists) appear to match the PDF row-for-row based on the provided extracts. The largest functional risks are (1) a missing product family referenced in the PDF (PTT), (2) a critical GDP configuration mismatch where the default frame depth should be 50 mm per the PDF example/standard, and (3) repeated semantic misuse of “max filter depth” for carbon-cylinder products where the PDF actually specifies cylinder length (450/600 mm). These can lead to incorrect recommendations and incompatibility outcomes.

Secondarily, several format and catalog-conformance issues exist: EXL and Filter Profil code formats don’t match the PDF’s hyphenation, PT material availability is missing RF as an on-request option per the section icon set, and multiple families (BFF/PFF/EXL) list broader material availability than the PDF text explicitly supports. Finally, one GDB weight cell (1800x900 short) is internally inconsistent but matches the PDF; it should be retained with a quality flag pending manufacturer clarification rather than silently corrected.

anthropic_opus.summary:
The Knowledge Graph demonstrates a high degree of fidelity to the PDF catalog. All 12 product families from the table of contents are present in the graph. The dimensional data across all product families (GDP: 35 sizes, GDB: 27 sizes, GDMI: 35 sizes, GDC: 12 sizes, GDC FLEX: 6 sizes, GDMI FLEX: 8 sizes, BFF: 5 sizes, PFF: 25 sizes, PT: 5 sizes, TT: 35 sizes, EXL: 8 sizes, Filter Profil: 36 variants) has been verified row-by-row against the PDF tables, and all numeric values (airflows, weights, dimensions, cartridge counts, module counts) match exactly with only one known discrepancy (GDB 1800x900 weight, which is flagged as a suspected PDF error).

The graph handles several PDF inconsistencies appropriately by documenting them as SOURCE_CONFLICT notes: the GDMI length discrepancy between text (550/600, 800/850) and table (600/650, 850/900), and the GDMI default material conflict between text (ZM) and example code (AZ). Material availability per product family is correctly modeled, with GDMI correctly limited to AZ/ZM and GDMI FLEX to FZ/AZ/ZM as shown by the PDF material icons.

The primary areas for improvement are: (1) adding metadata to distinguish between airflow values calculated at 1.5 m/s (GDP, PFF) versus recommended flows (GDC, GDC FLEX, GDMI FLEX), (2) clarifying the GDMI FLEX long variant description which incorrectly states '600mm cartridge or 450mm+polisfilter' when the PDF says '600 mm cylinder + polisfilter', and (3) verifying the PT material availability regarding the greyed-out RF icon. Overall, the graph scores well at approximately 72/100, with deductions primarily for missing metadata annotations rather than incorrect data.

openai.final_assessment: Across evaluators, the graph appears structurally strong on the major cabinet families and dimension tables, and it appropriately prioritizes tabular data when the PDF text conflicts (notably GDMI lengths). The main confirmed gaps are (1) a missing indexed accessory family (PTT) and (2) multiple SKU/code-format mismatches (EXL and Filter profil spacing/hyphenation), plus (3) a recurring semantic modeling issue where cartridge/cylinder length constraints for GDC/GDC FLEX/GDMI FLEX are represented as 'max filter depth' rather than cartridge length and polisfilter configuration rules. anthropic_opus.final_assessment: After peer review, the knowledge graph demonstrates solid structural coverage of all product families and their dimensional data. The most significant confirmed issues across evaluators are: (1) the semantic mislabeling of 'max filter depth' vs 'max cartridge length' for carbon filter cabinets GDC/GDC FLEX/GDMI FLEX, which could cause compatibility logic errors; (2) the incorrect description of GDMI FLEX length variant 1100/1150mm usage (PDF says '600mm cylinder + polisfilter', not '600mm or 450mm+polisfilter'); (3) the faithful reproduction of the GDB 1800x900 weight typo (36 kg instead of likely ~62 kg) which is correctly flagged; (4) the GDMI length source conflict between text and table values, handled appropriately by the graph; and (5) potential PT material availability gap for RF (stainless). The openai evaluator's finding about a missing PTT product family is incorrect - PTT on the contents page refers to PT (Plan Övergång), and the graph correctly models PT and TT separately. The code format findings about EXL and Filter Profil spacing were also incorrect - the PDF examples use spaces, matching the graph. The gemini_pro score of 98 is overly generous given the semantic issues with cartridge length modeling and the GDMI FLEX length description error. The openai score of 86 is reasonable but includes some invalid findings. A consensus score of 78 reflects the graph's strong dimensional data coverage offset by meaningful semantic and compatibility-logic issues that need correction before production use.

findings.recommendation: Refine construction taxonomy to distinguish 'housing_construction: SINGLE_WALL_UNINSULATED' from 'door_construction: DOUBLE_WALL_INSULATED' so queries don't misclassify GDB/GDC/GDC FLEX as fully uninsulated.

findings.description: Different product families use different airflow calculation bases, but the graph stores all airflow values without metadata distinguishing them. GDP and PFF use 'Flöde i m3/h vid 1,5 m/s' (at 1.5 m/s face velocity). GDB and GDMI use 'Flöde m3/h' (basis unspecified, derived from module count × 3400 m³/h). GDC, GDC FLEX, and GDMI FLEX use 'Rek. flöde m3/h' (recommended flow). These distinctions matter for engineering calculations.
findings.pdf_says: GDP page 6: 'Flöde i m3/h vid 1,5 m/s'. GDMI page 12: 'Flöde 3400 m3/h'. GDC page 14: 'Rek. flöde m3/h'. GDC FLEX page 16: 'Rek. flöde i m3/h'.
findings.graph_says: All airflow values stored as generic airflow without velocity or calculation basis metadata.
findings.recommendation: Add metadata attribute per family: GDP/PFF: flow_basis='calculated_at_1.5_m/s'; GDB/GDMI: flow_basis='module_based_3400_m3h_per_1x1'; GDC/GDC_FLEX/GDMI_FLEX: flow_basis='recommended'.

findings.description: The PDF explicitly states that GDB and GDMI use EXL excenter locking for filters with 25mm frames. This 25mm frame requirement is critical for filter compatibility but is not exposed as an explicit product-family attribute for filter acceptance logic.
findings.pdf_says: GDB page 8 and GDMI page 11: 'EXL excenterlåsning för kompakt och påsfilter med 25 mm ram.'
findings.graph_says: EXL dependency rule exists ('EXL requires 25mm filter frame') but product families GDB/GDMI do not expose accepted_filter_frame_thickness_mm=25 as a direct attribute.
findings.recommendation: Add explicit attribute on GDB and GDMI: accepted_filter_frame_thickness_mm=25. Ensure this is used by configurator and filter compatibility checks.

findings.description: The Sortiment page 3 shows GDMI filter max depths as 'Skåp 600/650mm Filter max 450mm' and 'Skåp 750/800mm Filter max 650mm'. However, the actual GDMI long length is 850/900 (not 750/800) per the dimension table on page 12. The sortiment page appears to have a typo for the second GDMI length. The graph correctly uses 850/900 with max filter depth 650mm.
findings.pdf_says: Sortiment page 3 GDMI: '600/650mm Filter max 450mm' and '750/800mm Filter max 650mm'. Dimension table page 12: 600/650 and 850/900.
findings.recommendation: No graph change needed. Document the sortiment page typo (750/800 should be 850/900 for GDMI).

findings.description: GDMI example code on page 11 uses material 'AZ' (GDMI-600x600-600-R-PG-AZ), but the descriptive text says 'tillverkas vanligen i ZM' (usually manufactured in ZM). The graph sets ZM as default and documents this as a SOURCE_CONFLICT. Both AZ and ZM are valid materials for GDMI; the conflict is only about which is the 'default'.
findings.pdf_says: Page 11: Example code: 'GDMI-600x600-600-R-PG-AZ'. Text: 'GDMI tillverkas vanligen i ZM.'
findings.recommendation: Acceptable handling. The text statement ('vanligen i ZM') is a stronger indicator of the default than the example code. Keep SOURCE_CONFLICT annotation.

recommendations: P1 CRITICAL: Correct GDMI FLEX long variant (1100/1150mm) description from '600mm cartridge or 450mm+polisfilter' to '600mm cylinder + polisfilter' per PDF page 18. Set 850/900 as 450mm cylinder only.

P2 MAJOR: Rename 'max_filter_depth' attribute to 'max_cartridge_length_mm' for all carbon filter cabinet families (GDC, GDC FLEX, GDMI FLEX). Model dual compatibility modes for GDC/GDC FLEX 900/950mm length (600mm cylinder alone OR 450mm cylinder + polisfilter).
P3 MAJOR: Review GDP default frame depth — PDF example table and code both use 50mm as the standard configuration. Consider setting default to 50mm rather than 25mm.
P4 MAJOR: Add SOURCE_ERROR annotation for GDMI FLEX weight table header duplication (both columns labeled 1100/1150). Document the interpretation logic.
P5 MAJOR: Verify GDC FLEX size '600x300' width/height mapping against the table columns (Bredd=300, Höjd=600) and resolve the label convention inconsistency.
P6 MAJOR: Retain GDB 1800x900 short-length weight (36 kg) with SUSPECTED_PDF_ERROR flag. Request manufacturer clarification.
P7 MINOR: Add airflow calculation basis metadata per product family (1.5 m/s for GDP/PFF, module-based for GDB/GDMI, recommended for GDC/GDC FLEX/GDMI FLEX).
P8 MINOR: Refine construction taxonomy to separate housing construction from door construction for GDB, GDC, and GDC FLEX families.
P9 MINOR: Verify PT material availability for RF (stainless) with manufacturer — greyed icon on page 22 is ambiguous.
P10 MINOR: Update flange option description to 'Fläns ohålad 40mm' across all families to match PDF specification.
final_report.summary:
The knowledge graph demonstrates strong overall fidelity to the MANN+HUMMEL HVAC Filterskåp PDF catalog (Version 01-09-2025). All 12 product families identified in the table of contents are present and correctly modeled. Dimensional data across all families — including 35 GDP sizes, 27 GDB sizes, 35 GDMI sizes, 12 GDC sizes, 6 GDC FLEX sizes, 8 GDMI FLEX sizes, 5 BFF sizes, 25 PFF sizes, 5 PT sizes, 35 TT sizes, 8 EXL sizes, and 36 Filter Profil variants — has been verified row-by-row with all numeric values (weights, airflows, dimensions, cartridge counts, module counts) matching the PDF exactly, with only one known weight discrepancy (GDB 1800x900) that is correctly flagged as a suspected PDF error.

The most significant issues requiring correction are: (1) the GDMI FLEX long variant description incorrectly states '600mm cartridge or 450mm+polisfilter' when the PDF clearly specifies '600mm cylinder + polisfilter' for the 1100/1150mm length; (2) a systematic semantic mislabeling where 'max filter depth' is used instead of 'max cartridge/cylinder length' for carbon filter cabinets, which could cause compatibility logic errors; and (3) the GDP default frame depth is set to 25mm while the PDF's example configuration table and code both use 50mm as the standard. The graph appropriately handles several PDF-internal conflicts (GDMI lengths, GDMI default material, GDMI FLEX weight header duplication) by prioritizing tabular data and documenting source conflicts.

Several evaluator findings were determined to be false positives during cross-review: the alleged missing 'PTT' product family (PTT on the contents page is simply the abbreviation for PT Plan Övergång, not a separate product), the EXL and Filter Profil code format spacing issues (the PDF examples use spaces matching the graph, not hyphens as claimed), and the GDMI stainless steel availability question (the PDF explicitly states 'Ej i Rostfritt' with only AZ and ZM icons shown). After resolving the confirmed findings — particularly the cartridge length semantics and GDMI FLEX description — the graph would achieve excellent production readiness.
